Lecture Demo 2 - Selecting data with SQL

  • First, access the SQL Cheatsheet

  • Return to the Global Dams dataset, delete the previous analysis filter, and toggle to DATA view in the CARTO interface. Point to the SQL panel utilizing the VALUES > SQL slider at bottom of panel.

  • Execute the following Queries utilizing SQL:

  • How many dams are there?

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM table
  • Which dams are in Japan?
SELECT * FROM table
WHERE country = 'Japan'
  • How many dams are mainly used for irrigation?
SELECT COUNT(*) FROM table
WHERE main_use = 'Irrigation'
  • How many dams were built before 1900?

Note: -99 values represent no year recorded for a particular dam in the dataset. We remove those records in the following query statement:

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM table
WHERE year < 1900 AND year != -99
  • Which dams were built after 2000?
SELECT * FROM table
WHERE  year > 2000

Lecture Demo 3 - Updating data with SQL

  • Clear all SQL statements from previous Demo 2.

  • Add a new column interactively in CARTO table view; name it quality_display, and make it a string field.

  • Put a more readable value in our new column based on the quality column. We can separate each value assignment by a ;:

UPDATE table
SET quality_display = 'Verified'
WHERE quality = '1: Verified';
UPDATE table
SET quality_display = 'Good'
WHERE quality = '2: Good';
UPDATE table
SET quality_display = 'Fair'
WHERE quality = '3: Fair';
UPDATE table
SET quality_display = 'Poor'
WHERE quality = '4: Poor';
UPDATE table
SET quality_display = 'Unreliable'
WHERE quality = '5: Unreliable'
  • Check that all records have been assigned the new qualitative values correctly, i.e. there are no resulting null values in the new quality_display column:
SELECT DISTINCT(quality_display) FROM table
